<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Amphipappus</i> <i>fremontii</i> and/or <i>Salvia</i> <i>funerea</i> is dominant or co-dominant in the shrub layer with <i>Ambrosia</i> <i>dumosa</i>, <i>Atriplex</i> <i>confertifolia</i>, <i>Atriplex</i> <i>hymenelytra</i>, <i>Brickellia</i> <i>microphylla</i>, <i>Echinocactus</i> <i>polycephalus</i>, <i>Ephedra</i> <i>nevadensis</i>, <i>Eriogonum</i> <i>fasciculatum</i>, <i>Larrea</i> <i>tridentata</i>, <i>Lepidium</i> <i>fremontii</i>, <i>Viguiera</i> <i>reticulata</i> and <i>Xylorhiza</i> <i>tortifolia</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text"> The emergent tree layer is sparse. The shrub layer is sparse to open.  The herbaceous layer is sparse to open. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Amphipappus fremontii </i>and/or <i>Salvia funerea</i> > 30% relative, if occurring together, and > 50% relative cover with other plants present (Evens et al. 2014).</li>
		
		<li><i>Amphipappus fremontii </i> > 2% absolute cover and > 50% relative cover (Thomas et al. 2004).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Steep montane slopes, ridges, cliffs, adjacent washes in sheltered canyons, and rocky eroding alluvial fans. Soils are shallow rocky, calcareous, and often with exposed bedrock and boulders. Parent material is primarily limestone and dolomite.  </div>
</div>

        
