<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Amphipappus fremontii</i> is found primarily in the Mojave Desert, from California to Arizona, Nevada, and Utah. It is a multi-branched clumping shrub with whitish stems and small gray-green leaves, and some stems are thorn-tipped. It has cyme-like clusters of lemon-yellow composite flowers (UCB 2017).<br/>
<br/>
<i>Salvia funerea</i> is endemic to the Mojave Desert, mostly found in the Death Valley region in California and Nevada, though it ranges south at least to the Bristol Mountains. It is whitish in appearance due to woolly hairs covering its stems and leaves, and its leaves are spine-tipped. It has deep blue-purple flowers that are surrounded by woolly spine-tipped sepals (UCB 2017). <br/>
<br/>
Both <i>Amphipappus fremontii</i> and <i>Salvia funerea</i> prefer rocky sites, and they are typically found on harsh, calcareous parent materials. Stands are often on rocky outcrops, and they can have high plant species diversity. While the alliance is known currently from the Death Valley region, it is likely to occur in other similar calcareous bedrock outcrops in the Mojave Desert and Southern Great Basin. Adjacent stands include those in the <i>Atriplex hymenelytra, Atriplex confertifolia, Ericameria paniculata,</i> and <i>Larrea tridentata - Ambrosia dumosa</i>  alliances. This alliance is similar ecologically to the <i>Atriplex confertifolia</i>, <i>Ephedra funerea</i>, and <i>Eriogonum wrightii - Eriogonum heermannii - Buddleja utahensis </i>alliances. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
