    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Ad, Al). The alliance occurs on limestone slopes to ridges, including the Bristol Mountains (J. Andre, pers. comm. 2011) as well as in the Funeral Mountains of Death Valley National Park (Evens et al. 2014). They are likely to occur in other subsections of the Mojave Desert on limestone-rich, rocky sites.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southeastern Great Basin</b> (341Fc-d, Ff). Stands occur in Death Valley National Park, generally in the mountains that have limestone and dolostone substrate, such as in the Cottonwood, Grapevine, and Panamint Mountains and the Last Chance and Saline Ranges (Evens et al. 2014)</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> This alliance is found in remote desert areas, and is protected in Death Valley National Park. Signs of desert bighorn sheep (<i>Ovis canadensis nelsoni</i>) are prevalent in the stands surveyed (Evens et al. 2014). However, some stands occur in areas impacted by mining. </div>
</div>

    

    

